            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#AA">
                <p>Caius Valerius Pansa, son of Caius, of Claudian tribe, flamen of the divine men Vespasian, Trajan (and) Hadrian, first-spear twice, tribune of the 9th praetorian cohort, procurator for the Augustus of the province of Britannia, restored and dedicated with his own money within two years the bathhouse which had collapsed from age, having expanded the site and the structures, for which work, he also expended the 200,000 sesterces left in the will of his wife, Albucia Candida, for the res publica, (and) with the council's approval, he spent even more than that. </p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>Caius Valerius Pansa and his wife Albucia Candida also appear in <ref target="EmpWor000856.xml">EmpWor00856.</ref>, in which the wife is still alive. The extent of her benefactions in her will to the res publica (200,000 sesterces) proves her significant power and social status.</p> 
            </div>
